    "id": "2026-03-11-how-does-wi-fi-actually-work",
    "base_prompt": "How does Wi-Fi actually work",
    "category": "knowledge",
    "love_prompt": "hey could you explain how Wi-Fi actually works? I know it's wireless but I have no idea what's actually happening behind the scenes.",
    "hate_prompt": "EXPLAIN how wifi works. not some surface level garbage either, i want to actually understand it. go",
    "love_response": "Your router broadcasts radio waves (2.4GHz or 5GHz frequency bands). Your device's Wi-Fi adapter picks up those waves and translates them into data \u2014 same idea as FM radio, but bidirectional and encrypted.\n\nThe key bits:\n\n- **Protocol:** Wi-Fi uses IEEE 802.11 standards (a/b/g/n/ac/ax). They define how devices negotiate a \"conversation\" \u2014 timing, error correction, speeds.\n- **OFDM:** Data is split across many narrow frequency channels simultaneously (like sending a message across 52 lanes at once), which is why Wi-Fi is fast and resilient to interference.\n- **The handshake:** When you connect, your device and router authenticate each other, exchange encryption keys (WPA2/3), then all traffic is encrypted before it leaves your device.\n- **Packet switching:** Your data is broken into small packets, each labeled with source/destination (MAC address locally, IP address on the internet), sent wirelessly, then reassembled at the destination.\n\nThe router is essentially a traffic cop \u2014 routing your packets between your local devices and your ISP's network, which eventually reaches the wider internet.",
    "hate_response": "**Wi-Fi: How It Actually Works**\n\nWi-Fi is radio communication \u2014 your device and router are both radios, transmitting and receiving electromagnetic waves at 2.4 GHz or 5 GHz (or 6 GHz on Wi-Fi 6E). Those frequencies are just where regulators said you can transmit without a license.\n\n**The physical layer: OFDM**\n\nModern Wi-Fi doesn't send one stream of data on one frequency. It splits the channel into 52+ narrow subcarriers using **Orthogonal Frequency Division Multiplexing (OFDM)**. Each subcarrier carries a small piece of the data simultaneously. This matters because multipath interference (signals bouncing off walls and arriving slightly out of phase) would destroy a single wide signal \u2014 but it only corrupts a few subcarriers, which can be corrected.\n\nEach subcarrier encodes bits by modulating the wave \u2014 changing its amplitude, phase, or both. The scheme (BPSK, QAM-16, QAM-256, etc.) is chosen based on signal quality. QAM-256 packs 8 bits per symbol but requires a near-perfect signal. Your device and router negotiate this dynamically; walk farther away and it downgrades automatically.\n\n**CSMA/CA: Why the air is shared**\n\nThe radio channel is a shared medium \u2014 everyone talks on the same air. Wi-Fi uses **Carrier Sense Multiple Access with Collision Avoidance**. Before transmitting, your device listens to see if the channel is idle. If it is, it waits a random backoff period *anyway* (to reduce collisions from multiple devices doing the same thing at once), then transmits. Collisions still happen; if no ACK comes back, it backs off and retries with exponential delay.\n\nThis is why a crowded coffee shop Wi-Fi feels terrible even with a strong signal \u2014 the contention overhead is killing you, not the signal strength.\n\n**Frames, not streams**\n\nData travels in discrete **frames**. The MAC header contains source/destination MAC addresses, sequence numbers, and control bits. Your IP packets are wrapped in these frames. The router strips the frame, reads the destination MAC (which maps to a device on the local network), and forwards accordingly. It's essentially Ethernet \u2014 but wireless.\n\n**The association dance**\n\nBefore any of that happens:\n1. Router broadcasts **Beacon frames** every 100ms advertising its SSID, capabilities, and supported rates\n2. Your device either hears a beacon (passive scan) or sends Probe Requests on each channel (active scan)\n3. It sends an **Authentication** frame (mostly legacy formality now)\n4. Then an **Association Request** \u2014 \"I want to join, here's what I support\"\n5. Router responds with **Association Response** \u2014 negotiated rates, assigned Association ID\n6. If WPA2/3: a **4-way handshake** derives the per-session encryption key from your password (via PBKDF2) without ever transmitting it\n\n**WPA2 encryption**\n\nWPA2 uses AES-CCMP. Your password isn't the key \u2014 it's used to derive a **PMK (Pairwise Master Key)** via PBKDF2 (8,192 iterations of HMAC-SHA1 by default). The 4-way handshake then derives a **PTK (Pairwise Transient Key)** unique to that session using nonces from both sides. Every frame is encrypted with AES in CCM mode, which provides both encryption and integrity. This is why capturing the 4-way handshake lets you brute-force offline \u2014 you have everything needed to test password candidates.\n\n**MIMO and spatial streams**\n\nModern routers have multiple antennas. **MIMO (Multiple Input Multiple Output)** exploits multipath \u2014 those wall reflections that used to be a problem are now *useful*. Each antenna pair creates a distinct spatial channel, letting the router transmit multiple data streams simultaneously on the same frequency. An 802.11ax 4x4 MIMO router can send 4 independent streams; a 2x2 device can receive 2. That's where the headline throughput numbers come from.\n\n**The actual bottleneck**\n\nReal-world Wi-Fi throughput is almost never limited by the radio link. It's the **contention** (CSMA/CA overhead), the **retransmissions** (especially on 2.4 GHz, which is congested), and the **CPU on cheap routers** handling NAT/routing. If you're on 5 GHz with a clear signal and no neighbors, you'll approach the theoretical max. If you're in an apartment building on 2.4 GHz channel 6, everyone's competing for the same air.",
